    answer: 3,
    explanation: "Pelvic lymph nodes with short-axis diameter greater than 8–10 mm on CT or MRI are considered suspicious for metastatic involvement in prostate cancer staging based on size criteria.\n\nSize criteria miss microscopic involvement; PSMA PET-CT improves detection independent of size by targeting prostate-specific membrane antigen on cancer cells regardless of nodal size on conventional imaging.\n\n5 mm is normal size; 15, 20 and 30 mm represent overtly enlarged nodes with high probability of involvement but lower thresholds detect earlier disease for treatment planning.\n\n<i>(Core Radiology by Jacob C. Mandell)</i>"
